Java follows a reverse domain name convention for package names. This ensures uniqueness and avoids conflicts.
Rules:

Start with your domain name in reverse:

Example: If your domain is example.com, your base package should be com.example.

Use lowercase letters only:

Package names are case-sensitive; lowercase avoids confusion.

Add project/module name:

Example: com.example.myapp

Add feature-specific sub-packages:

Example: com.example.myapp.service, com.example.myapp.model

Avoid special characters and spaces:

Only letters, digits, and underscores are allowed.

Keep names short and meaningful:

Use descriptive names for clarity

// File: MyPackage/MyClass.java
package MyPackage; // declare package at top

public class MyClass {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Hello from MyPackage!");
    }
}

Compliation

javac -d . MyClass.java

-d . tells the compiler to create the folder structure for the package.